When TableItem's setBackground was called twice, CPU time was eaten up.

package org.eclipse.swt.snippets;

import org.eclipse.swt.SWT;
import org.eclipse.swt.widgets.Display;
import org.eclipse.swt.widgets.Event;
import org.eclipse.swt.widgets.Listener;
import org.eclipse.swt.widgets.Shell;
import org.eclipse.swt.widgets.Table;
import org.eclipse.swt.widgets.TableItem;

public class Snippet53 {
	public static void main(String[] args) {
		final Display display = new Display();
		Shell shell = new Shell(display);
		final Table table = new Table(shell, SWT.BORDER | SWT.MULTI);
		table.setSize(200, 200);
		for (int i = 0; i < 128; i++) {
			TableItem item = new TableItem(table, SWT.NONE);
			item.setText("Item " + i);
		}
		final Listener paint = new Listener() {
			public void handleEvent(Event event) {
				switch (event.type) {
				case SWT.PaintItem:
					TableItem item = (TableItem) event.item;
					item.setBackground(display.getSystemColor(SWT.COLOR_CYAN));
					item.setBackground(display.getSystemColor(SWT.COLOR_GREEN));
					break;
				}
			}
		};
		table.addListener(SWT.PaintItem, paint);
		shell.pack();
		shell.open();
		while (!shell.isDisposed()) {
			if (!display.readAndDispatch())
				display.sleep();
		}
		display.dispose();
	}
}

Imagine exception class A, with subclasses B and C.

public class D {

/**
 * @throws B
 *   if something B happens.
 * @throws C
 *   if something C happens.
 */
public void myMethod() throws A {
}
}

So myMethod throws the superclass, but in javadoc says it may throw the subclasses. Organize imports, and you'll see that imports for B and C are added to the file. This is unexpected. Save the file. The compiler does not complain about the imports for B and C (which should be unused). I don't think the import code should ever look in the javadoc.

I haven't tested to see if B and C have to be related to A in order for this bug to occur - I suspect not.

I think this is a core bug, not ui, because it affects not only the organize imports action but also the compiler (since the unneeded imports are not flagged as such).

